      "content": "I think the \"risk\" factor is largely about the candidate's ability to navigate the nuances of US corporate culture, which can be quite different from what they're used to in China. It's not necessarily about their technical training, but rather about their ability to adapt to the social dynamics, communication styles, and power structures of a US-based company.\n\nIn that sense, a hiring manager might view Malik as a safer bet because he's from a local university and has likely had more exposure to the US tech industry. He may be seen as more familiar with the local customs, values, and expectations, which could make it easier for him to integrate into the company culture.\n\nWei, on the other hand, may be viewed as a bit of a wild card, someone who's coming from a very different cultural background and may require more guidance and support to adjust to the US environment. This could be a concern for a hiring manager who's looking for a candidate who can hit the ground running and lead teams effectively from day one.",
